					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Abendar’s Wizard Training Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:legendzero@earthlink.net">David G.</a> | 
		            2/12/2003 12:01:31 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Before I begin, let me introduce myself. I am Abendar Scorchand a wizard, currently of the 34th Power, and a High Elf. I have learned through experience a few rough lessons. Some of what I have to say I learned through trial and error and some from other wizards and their wise counsel, and following tradition I am here to pass on what I have learned. I will try my best not to make your experience boring by telling you where to go or what to hunt but since all my accumulated knowledge is related to my experience, I WILL give you examples&#8230; lots of them so be prepared, for here begins the lesson&#8230;.<BR>
<BR>
I know many of you who will seek out guides such as this one will already HAVE a wizard, but for those haven&#8217;t yet here are some things to remember when creating your wizard.<BR>
1.	It&#8217;s a class of brains not brawn! That being the case I HIGHLY recommend putting as many points as you can spare into INT. Your INT determines how much mana you have, and as any wizard will tell you, mana is life for us&#8230;and death for them.<BR>
2.	Secondly any extra points would be wisely spent in AGI. Having a high AGI rating makes you harder to hit, especially once you get the Dodge skill. You could put those points in other categories for melee damage or HP but I&#8217;d rather not get hit when monsters are doing 65 points of damage per hit, than have extra 15 HP; would rather have that last little bit of mana for an Evacuate spell or to finish the monster off than have a few more damage points on melee (which you wont be doing much of past level 12).<BR>
3.	Look at each race possible for your wizard before choosing one. I picked High Elf for the vision enhancements and initial faction status.<BR>
<BR>
Here&#8217;s a few of the wizard basics:<BR>
At low levels things will be a little on the rough side. You wont ever seem to have enough money and melee-wise you will be hard pressed to keep up, but DON&#8217;T GIVE UP! Here are a few ideas on how to put all that INT to good use.<BR>
1.	Test your skills! Work on any skill you think you will enjoy.  Some time spent fishing can turn some free time into a few extra gold for spells. I got myself a sewing kit and hunted spiders for silks. Why? Because until you are powerful enough for some long quests or have several hundred plat for equipment, the best armor you can get will be hand made! I tailored my own raw silk armor and after I had all I could wear I tailored armor for other casters for some extra pp for spells. Most zones in the game have spiders of some kind and even up to level 13 or so the giant spiders will give you xp AND silks for tailoring. Look around your starting area and see what other critters drop that might be good fuel for a profitable skill!<BR>
2.	There are lots of little things that can turn out to be big bucks in stacks. Bone chips sell well, so do bat wings, silk swatches, various reagent gemstones etc etc. Keep an eye out for opportunities.<BR>
3.	Surfs&#8217; up! One really valuable yet often overlooked skill is swimming. Spend some time boosting that swimming skill whenever you can. Having a high swimming skill has saved my hide more times than I can count. The higher your skill level the faster you can swim. <BR>
4.	Also don&#8217;t forget to practice sense heading. It can really help out if you know a general direction but no specific loc. For example if you know you were going east when you died you can retrace your steps to your corpse, but only if you can figure out which way is east&#8230;..<BR>
5.	Homeward bound! Put that level 4 Gate spell to good use for some extra cash. Venture to a remote area and offer to make bank runs for groups. I once made over 300pp in several hours by doing this. The campers would give me the gold silver and copper and I&#8217;d gate home and hop into the bank to exchange it for platinum and make the run back to their camp (sense heading came in EXTREMELY handy on several of these runs) and they gave me a percentage of the cash loot. <BR>
6.	At level 5 I highly recommend doing the Cubert quest in Queynos. At level 5 u should make some xp and turning in the dress Cubert drops can score you some decent +INT earrings.<BR>
7.	Study! Spend some time out of the game researching equipment and quests. It&#8217;ll make you a popular travel companion when you come up with suggestions on where to hunt or what to camp. And knowing what zones have available benefits everyone. For instance it was pretty easy to convince my group from FM hit up Soluseks Eye when I told them there was 13% xp bonus in the zone and that one of the monsters I wanted to camp there dropped some great gear.<BR>
8.	Keep your friends close! Early on you will be able to solo with a fair amount of success but as you increase in level you will need to rely more on others and having friends really comes in handy. Around level 10 I ventured into Crushbone on Faydwer and at level 34 I STILL group with some of the same people. Why? I took the time to keep in touch when they were online. Even if we didn&#8217;t get together to hunt I&#8217;d send a tell to find out their latest. And a few of the people who passed me in level have given me some decent hand-me-down items and loot. <BR>
9.	Vary your routine! To keep things from getting too boring change things up. Spend some time traveling or doing a quest for some cool gear or building up a particular skill. I made some great money at level 29 spending hours just teleporting people from place to place and making funny hotkeys.<BR>
<BR>
The Wizard Tactical Guide.<BR>
With low HP, poor AC, almost no buffs, and pets that don&#8217;t fight, we wizards aren&#8217;t very versatile in combat. So the question is, &#8216;What ARE we good for?&#8221;. The answer is simple: Wizards were built to dish out damage from a distance. This is a GUIDE not a rulebook. A lot of these tactics I learned from Auxantuar&#8217;s Guide to Wizard Combat and Tactics and have modified them and expanded them as they worked for me. Feel free to change your tactics as you see fit but these ideas will make you a formidable killing machine. Nobody knows combat like the military so I have included a lot of military-type phrases and ideas. <BR>
<BR>
&#183;	The 6 &#8216;P&#8217;s &#8211; Proper preparation prevents piss poor performance. Yes it&#8217;s a military saying, but here&#8217;s why its important: You cant recharge your mana if you are out of food/drink. You cant fight without mana. Pretty simple but there are several things you should make sure you have ready before joining your group and trying to take out the bad guys.<BR>
1.	Essential Inventory- Food, water, regents, backpacks and any special gear you think might come in handy.<BR>
2.	Spells- Organize and memorize the best spells for the situation<BR>
3.	Hotkeys- I&#8217;ll get into specifics here in a minute but hotkeys are VITAL for wizard combat.<BR>
&#183;	Think &#8216;Artillery&#8217;! &#8211; You have probably heard the high AC classes like warriors called &#8216;tanks&#8217; before so just think of wizards as artillery. In the world of military machines there is what is called a Mobile Artillery Track. It&#8217;s really like a big truck or all terrain vehicle with racks and racks of mortars on top. Now when the fighting starts the tanks wade into the close range combat and their thick armor makes it possible but the artillery stays OUT of the way and lobs large mortar rounds from a very long distance. THAT is just like what we wizards should do.  Don&#8217;t get in close, we don&#8217;t take damage well and spells can be easy to interrupt, so stand back and toss some heavy explosions in.<BR>
&#183;	Don&#8217;t get carried away. As much as I enjoy nuking an enemy into oblivion ( and I REALLY enjoy that ) I had to learn to pace myself. Don&#8217;t forget that this is a group effort. Let the tanks soak up some damage, after all that&#8217;s why they are the tanks,  but if they get into trouble help bail them out! Root and nuke the baddie into the afterlife.<BR>
&#183;	Communication &#8211; Don&#8217;t forget to talk to your group. Keep them up on your mana status and joke about how your big nuke does XX damage. Pay attention to their input as well. If the creature is already rooted don&#8217;t waste the mana on a root spell. Adjust your tactics to the situation based on who has mana, who has hp, how many baddies are incoming, how many are getting away, if someone is forced to retreat or zone, this is important Need To Know information&#8230; and you NEED TO KNOW!<BR>
&#183;	Work like a unit &#8211; Don&#8217;t be afraid to step in occasionally and smack a target with your staff, (if nothing else it always gives me a chance to joke about my lack of damage) but be smart about it! If the healer is low on mana and the tank is losing ground, don&#8217;t waste time swinging a staff,  blast away! Or if you&#8217;re out of mana sit and med till you can cast a decent damage spell. Root or nuke escaping targets so the tanks don&#8217;t have to chase and split up the group. <BR>
The wonderful world of Hotkeys &#8211; These hotkeys will revolutionize your role in group combat.<BR>
1.	I&#8217;m in some trouble here! (and /y command) &#8211; Use this hotkey only in an emergency. If you over-nuke a target and it turns from attacking the tank to come after you, don&#8217;t use this key. The tanks will follow it and if you just stay calm and don&#8217;t run the tanks should have its attention back pretty fast. On the other hand if a creature spawns and attacks you and the rest of your group is engaged in combat, use the hotkey to get some help.<BR>
2.	Low on Mana or LOM &#8211; If you&#8217;re in the middle of combat and find yourself down to 20% mana (one mana bubble) hit this key to let your team know you wont be able to dish out any significant damage. <BR>
3.	RETREATING or BACKING OFF!! &#8211; If the battle seems to be turning against your group and you are out of mana and there&#8217;s no place to med and no one to beat this monster off you then maybe a retreat is in order. Don&#8217;t use this key to tell the group what to do! Just use it  to sum up. <BR>
4.	Assisting %t (and /assist command) &#8211; Target the group puller and when he or she announces incoming baddies use this key. First of all it will help keep you targeted on the same target as the tank (if you are the only one attacking a target you might attract too much of its attention, so try to keep to follow the tanks lead) and second of all it will encourage others to assist and focus on ONE target. If everyone is attacking the same baddie, it wont last very long  and then the group can move on the any added pulls or pops. <BR>
5.	Medding up! &#8211; Use this hotkey to inform your team that you are going to sit and med. Don&#8217;t be afraid to med during combat if you&#8217;re low on mana. I usually cast once and sit for a few seconds before popping up to fire off another spell. Just think of it as reloading. Or you can add this phrase onto your LOM hotkey since they usually go together.<BR>
6.	Incoming Nuke &#8211; Since I hate to waste mana on a spell that goes off just a second too late I use this hotkey (or funnier versions of it) to warn my party that I&#8217;m about to kill the target so they don&#8217;t cast at the same time.<BR>
7.	%t is rooted! &#8211; I use this hotkey if I&#8217;m in charge of keep the creature rooted or slowed.<BR>
Now I know these all sound self-explanatory but knowing when to use them (and actually using them) can save lives! Do what you have to do to stay alive, but don&#8217;t be a coward. Be creative! Down in the basements of HighKeep it&#8217;s easy for healers to run out of mana too soon and tanks to get low on life. I have been known to use my huge nukes to pull MoBs off of a tank long enough for the group to get things under control. A couple times I have died in the attempt but I have NEVER had a group dislike my character and they almost always listen when I make a suggestion. Why? Because they know I&#8217;m serious and that I&#8217;m trying to help the group. They know I&#8217;m willing to sacrifice myself to save the group but the smart thing is to not have to.  I hope that this guide has given you some ideas to play with and try out. Safe journeys and happy hunting, friends! Class dismissed!<BR>
<BR>
-Abendar Scorchand, Luclin Server
